data.content:
Yes — for simple inline data, use `[DataRow]` instead. It's more concise and type-safe:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DataRow("valid@email.com", true)]
[DataRow("invalid", false)]
[DataRow("", false)]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}
```

**When to use each approach:**

- **`[DataRow]`** — best for simple compile-time constants (strings, bools, ints).
- **`[DynamicData]`** — needed when test data involves non-constant objects (e.g., class instances, computed values). If you stick with it, you can improve type safety by using tuples:

```csharp
public static IEnumerable<(string Input, bool Expected)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```
